{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 15:51:30.072635", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — enterprise OSPF network with central DHCP/DNS and server farm\nSummary\n- Core routing and server-side infrastructure appear healthy: FRR/OSPF routes for server networks and host subnets are present; server access router and servers (DHCP, DNS, load‑balancer, web servers) have correct IPv4 addresses and routes.\n- DHCP server is receiving requests and issuing leases for many host subnets.\n- However, a subset of access hosts are unable to send IP traffic (ping returned \"Network is unreachable\") because their network interfaces are up but have no IPv4 address or route configured locally. Evidence indicates the DHCP exchange completed (leases exist) but the client-side networking on those hosts did not apply the assigned IPs. This prevents those hosts from reaching the DHCP/DNS/web infrastructure even though the rest of the network advertises and routes the subnets.\n\nKey findings and evidence\n1) Host-side symptom: inability to reach infrastructure from sampled hosts\n- When pinging infrastructure from several sample hosts (host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1) the ping command returned:\n  - \"ping: connect: Network is unreachable\"\n  - This indicates no usable IP/route on the host for those destination prefixes.\n\n2) Host interface state but no IPv4 address\n- host_1_1_1_1: get_host_net_config shows eth0 present, UP and RUNNING, but ip addr output contains no \"inet\" (no IPv4 assigned) and there are no routes:\n  - ifconfig: eth0 up; ip_addr: eth0 exists but no inet line; ip_route: empty\n- host_2_1_1_1: same pattern — interface up but no IPv4 address, ip_route empty.\n  - (Both hosts show RX/TX packet counters on the interface — link is up and L2 is passing traffic.)\n\n3) DHCP client and lease file on host show lease was received\n- host_1_1_1_1 runs dhclient (ps shows \"dhclient -d eth0\") and /var/lib/dhcp/dhclient.leases contains a valid lease:\n  - fixed-address 10.1.1.25\n  - option routers 10.1.1.1\n  - option domain-name-servers 10.200.0.2\n- The DHCP server's lease database also shows active leases for many hosts (including that host), confirming that DHCP requests and server responses are traversing the network.\n\n4) Server and routing plane healthy\n- dhcp_server: eth0 = 10.200.0.8/24; route table contains default via 10.200.0.1.\n- dns_server: eth0 = 10.200.0.2/24.\n- server_access_router: br0 = 10.200.0.1/24 and an uplink IP (172.16.0.23/31) present.\n- router_core_1: routing table shows OSPF‑advertised routes for the host subnets and server networks (10.1.x.0/24 and 10.2.x.0/24 present via expected next hops).\n- router_dist_1_1: br0 = 10.1.1.1/24 present and OSPF routes for other subnets via 172.16.0.6; its ip_route lists 10.1.1.0/24 as directly connected.\n\n5) Mixed reachability across hosts\n- The reachability scan shows many hosts with valid IP assignments and successful pings (some hosts in 10.1.4.x etc had successful ping results), so the problem is not global; it affects a subset of hosts.\n\nAffected devices / scope\n- Confirmed affected: host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 (examples); these hosts show:\n  - Interface up at L2\n  - DHCP client present and lease recorded locally\n  - No IPv4 address present on the interface and no IP route\n  - \"Network is unreachable\" on outgoing ping attempts\n- Potentially affected: other hosts that the reachability tool marked as null/unknown in mapping; the issue appears to be intermittent/host‑specific rather than a systemic router or DHCP-server failure.\n\nProbable root cause(s)\n- Most likely: client-side network stack / DHCP client not applying the obtained lease to the interface.\n  - Rationale: DHCP server is issuing leases (leases present both on server and locally); L2 connectivity exists (eth0 is up and frames are being transmitted/received) but the kernel interface lacks the assigned IPv4 address and route. That points to a failure in the DHCP client’s step that programs the interface (or to a local networking configuration preventing the address from being applied).\n- Less likely (but possible) explanations to consider:\n  - The DHCP client was invoked in a mode that prevented it from writing addr/route (e.g., running in debug-only or missing hook scripts), or the client failed to run the set‑up scripts (permission/utility missing).\n  - Local configuration or scripts that immediately remove or override the address after DHCP (for instance, network manager or a startup script).\n  - Network namespace / containerization causing dhclient to write leases in one namespace while the interface used by the host process is in another (less likely in this topology but possible).\n  - An intermittent or partial switch/access-layer issue that allows DHCP DISCOVER/OFFER/ACK exchange but prevents final ARP/neighbor/assignment at the host (evidence favors client-side software issue rather than L2 problem because RX/TX counters and leases exist).\n\nAdditional evidence / outputs (selected)\n- host_1_1_1_1: ps shows dhclient -d eth0 running; dhclient.leases shows lease for 10.1.1.25; ip addr shows no IPv4 assigned; ip route empty.\n- dhcp_server: eth0 = 10.200.0.8/24; its leases file contains many active leases across 10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x ranges.\n- router_core_1: FRR show ip route shows OSPF entries for 10.1.1.0/24 and other host subnets via expected next hops; OSPF adjacency and route advertisement present.\n- server_access_router: bridging present, br0 = 10.200.0.1/24; server hosts have expected IPs (web_server_0..3, load_balancer, dns_server, dhcp_server).\n\nImplications / impact\n- Hosts that do not have IPv4 addresses applied cannot reach DNS, DHCP renewal (beyond L2), or any server/service. Where DHCP or DNS is required for service discovery or authentication, these hosts are effectively offline at L3.\n- Since the routing plane and server network are healthy, the issue is localized to affected hosts and their host‑side network configuration.\n\nSuggested follow-up diagnostic checks (non‑remediative)\n- On an affected host, capture dhclient stdout/log to confirm whether dhclient attempted the interface configuration step and whether it reported any error while invoking ip/ifconfig (look for error messages in syslog or dhclient debug output).\n- Check for presence/permissions of the DHCP client hook scripts (e.g., /sbin/ifupdown hooks, /etc/dhcp/dhclient-enter-hooks.d or /etc/dhcp/dhclient-exit-hooks.d) and whether they succeeded.\n- Verify that the host has the expected ip/ifconfig utilities and can accept programmatic address assignment (check dmesg/syslog for kernel messages rejecting address assignment).\n- Check whether any local network manager or custom script is overwriting or clearing DHCP assignments after dhclient runs.\n- For completeness, run an ARP/pcap capture on the access switch port or router distribution port for an affected host to confirm DHCP ACK packets and any subsequent ARP/neighbor activity.\n\nConclusion\n- The network control plane (FRR/OSPF) and server farm are functioning correctly and DHCP is issuing leases. The primary anomaly is on a subset of hosts where DHCP leases are received but not applied — i.e., the host network stack (DHCP client → kernel interface configuration) is failing to program the assigned IPv4 address and routes. This is the most likely root cause of the observed \"Network is unreachable\" pings from those hosts.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 79291, "output_tokens": 4386, "total_tokens": 83677, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 78592}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2624}}}
